{"cursor":"11910","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Herpes gladiatorum' is one of the most infectious of herpes-caused diseases,\nand is transmissible by skin-to-skin contact. The disease was first described in\nthe 1960s in the [[New England Journal of Medicine]]. It is caused by cutaneous\ninfection with Human Herpes Simplex Virus type 1 (HSV-1), which more commonly causes oral herpes (cold sores).\nAnother strain, HSV-2 usually causes genital herpes, although the strains are\nvery similar and either can cause herpes in any location.\n\nWhile the disease is commonly passed through normal human contact, it is\nstrongly associated with contact sports â outbreaks in sporting clubs being\nrelatively common. Other names for the disease are\n'herpes rugbiorum' or \"'scrumpox'\" (after rugby football),\n\"'wrestler's herpes'\" or \"'mat pox'\" (after wrestling). In one of the largest\noutbreaks ever among high-school wrestlers at a four week intensive training\ncamp, HSV was identified in 60 of 175 wrestlers. Lesions were on the head in 73\nper cent of the wrestlers, the extremities in 42 per cent, and the trunk in 28\nper cent. {{cite journal |author=Belongia EA, Goodman JL,\nHolland EJ, et al |title=An outbreak of herpes gladiatorum at a high-school\nwrestling camp |journal=N. Engl. J. Med. |volume=325 |issue=13 |pages=906â10\n|year=1991 |month=September |pmid=1652687 |doi=\n10.1056/NEJM199109263251302|url=http://content.nejm.org/cgi/content/abstract/32-\n   5/13/906 }} Physical symptoms sometimes recur in the skin. Previous adolescent HSV-1 seroconversion would\n   preclude most herpes gladiatorum, but being that stress and trauma are\n   recognized triggers, such a person would be likely to infect others.\n","linknr":362,"url":"Herpes_gladiatorum","recorded":1363454970,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Herpes_gladiatorum&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Herpes_gladiatorum&action=edit","//en.wikipedia.org/apple-touch-icon.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/fa